                    <h6 class="font-normal text-gray-600 text-base leading-tight tracking-wider pb-9 md:pb-8">business decision records</h6>
                    <p class="text-black text-base leading-normal md:text-xl lg:text-2xl md:leading-snug font-light pb-4 md:pb-7">Business Decision Records (BDRs) are documents written to capture significant strategic decisions, in the style of software architecture decision records. </p>
                    <p class="text-black text-base leading-normal md:text-xl lg:text-2xl md:leading-snug font-light pb-4 md:pb-7">We have found ADRs to be very useful to retrospect and introspect on our software projects. BDRs are an attempt to bring that utility to the arc of our business.</p>
                    <p class="text-black text-base leading-normal md:text-xl lg:text-2xl md:leading-snug font-light">BDRs have some distinct properties: First and foremost, they are immutable. Once a BDR is written, it cannot be modified or removed. To alter or "undo" a BDR, nilenso must create another new, immutable BDR. Second, they are historical. Because BDRs cannot be modified, they do not represent a policy and they are not a living document. They may of course point to a policy or living document which represents the most current version of the decision. BDRs are used to identify decision points for high-level strategy, policy, and company principles. They should not be used to describe or document specific actions the company or its employees take.</p>
                </div>
